# Onshape Features (BTM* envelope)

A Part Studio's regenerable history is its **Feature List**: an ordered array of
features (sketch, extrude, fillet, …) that recompute top-to-bottom into geometry.
Every feature read or written through the REST API is a tree of versioned
`BT*`/`BTM*` types. This file is the deep-dive on that envelope; the high-level
"change a depth and verify" recipe lives in @onshape/api.

## Model

- Addressed by `did/{wvm}/{wvmid}/eid` (see @onshape/partstudios). **Reads** accept
  any coordinate (`/w/`, `/v/`, `/m/`); **writes** (add/update/delete) target a
  workspace `/w/` only.
- The feature endpoints sit under the Part Studio element:
  `…/partstudios/d/{did}/{wvm}/{wvmid}/e/{eid}/features…`.
- The Feature List has a **rollback bar**: features above the bar are computed,
  features below are deferred. `GET features` returns the current `rollbackIndex`;
  `POST …/features/rollback` (body: a string index) moves it. Pass
  `rollbackBarIndex` (query) to many GETs to read state *as of* a position.
- Edits are **optimistic-concurrency** gated by microversion. `GET features`
  returns `sourceMicroversion`; echo it back on a write. If the document advanced
  underneath you that's a **microversion skew** — `rejectMicroversionSkew: true`
  makes the write fail rather than silently apply onto a moved base. The script
  passes back `sourceMicroversion` with `rejectMicroversionSkew: false`.

## Endpoints

| METHOD path | purpose |
| --- | --- |
| `GET …/e/{eid}/features` | Full feature tree: `features[]`, `defaultFeatures[]`, `imports[]`, `featureStates`, `rollbackIndex`, `sourceMicroversion`, `isComplete`. Query: `featureId` (one feature), `rollbackBarIndex`, `includeGeometryIds`, `noSketchGeometry`. |
| `GET …/e/{eid}/featurespecs` | `featureSpecs[]` (BTFeatureSpec-129) — the declared parameter schema of each available feature type. |
| `POST …/e/{eid}/features` | **Add** a feature. Body wraps one `BTMFeature-134` in a `BTFeatureDefinitionCall-1406`. Resp: the created `feature` + `featureState`. |
| `POST …/e/{eid}/features/featureid/{fid}` | **Update** the feature `{fid}`. Same wrapper; send the WHOLE feature back. |
| `DELETE …/e/{eid}/features/featureid/{fid}` | **Delete** feature `{fid}`. Resp is the bare envelope (no `feature`). |
| `POST …/e/{eid}/features/updates` | Batch update: `features[]` of `BTMFeature-134` in one call. |
| `POST …/e/{eid}/features/rollback` | Move the rollback bar; body is a string index. Resp carries the new `rollbackIndex`. |

## The BTM* type system

Every node carries two discriminators that must agree:
- `btType` — the **serialization** tag, `"<TypeName>-<number>"` (e.g.
  `BTMFeature-134`). This is what the wire protocol keys on; the number is the
  stable type id, the name is the class.
- `typeName` — the **logical** type name a feature/parameter advertises
  (e.g. a feature's `featureType: "extrude"`). `btType` selects the struct;
  `featureType`/`parameterId` select which feature/field within it.

The nesting, outermost in:

- **`BTFeatureDefinitionCall-1406`** — the write envelope. Fields: `feature`
  (one `BTMFeature-134`), `sourceMicroversion`, `rejectMicroversionSkew`,
  `serializationVersion`, `libraryVersion`. Add/update both POST this shape.
- **`BTMFeature-134`** — one feature. Key fields: `featureId` (stable id used in
  the `/featureid/{fid}` path), `featureType` (`"extrude"`, `"fillet"`, …),
  `name` (display name), and `parameters[]` — an array of `BTMParameter*`.
- **`BTMParameter*`** — one parameter, tagged by `btType`, addressed by
  `parameterId`. The subtypes that matter:
  - **`BTMParameterQuantity-147`** — a value with units, carried as a string
    `expression` (`"25 mm"`, `"#width"`, `"2*sin(30 deg)"`). FeatureScript
    evaluates it, so it can reference variables and math, not just literals.
  - **`BTMParameterQueryList-148`** — a list of geometry references (`queries`):
    the faces/edges/sketch regions the feature operates on (see Queries below).
  - **`BTMParameterBoolean-144`** — a `value: true|false` (e.g. "flip
    direction").
  - **`BTMParameterEnum-145`** — a `value` string out of an `enumName` set
    (e.g. `endBound: "BLIND" | "UP_TO_NEXT" | …`).
  - **`BTMParameterString-149`** — a free-text `value`.

**Send the whole feature back.** Update is a replace, not a patch: the server
reconstructs the feature from exactly the `parameters[]` you POST. A parameter
you omit is **reset to its default**, not left alone. So the safe edit is
GET → mutate one field in place → POST the same object back (which is precisely
what `onshape_edit.py` does — it mutates `depth["expression"]` on the fetched
feature and reposts that feature unchanged otherwise).

`imports[]` (`BTMImport-136`) and `defaultFeatures[]` (the origin planes / default
datums) come back on GET as context; you don't normally repost them.

## Queries — how a parameter points at geometry

Geometry-valued parameters (`BTMParameterQueryList-148`) don't store coordinates;
they store **queries** that re-resolve against the current model each regen.
Two flavours:
- **Deterministic ids** — opaque stable ids for a specific face/edge/vertex,
  surfaced by `GET features?includeGeometryIds=true` and resolvable across
  microversions via the Part Studio `idtranslations` endpoint
  (see @onshape/partstudios).
- **Query expressions** — a FeatureScript query (e.g. "all faces created by
  feature X", "the sketch region named Y"). These survive edits that would
  invalidate a raw id, which is why Onshape prefers them. Authoring queries is a
  FeatureScript concern — see @onshape/featurescript.

A numeric parameter like `depth` is a plain `BTMParameterQuantity-147` and needs
no query; you only touch queries when the feature must bind to model geometry.

## Shapes

Real **update-feature** request body for an extrude depth change, as built by
`onshape_edit.py` (`update_feature` wraps the GET'd `BTMFeature-134`; depth's
`expression` is the one field mutated). POST to
`…/partstudios/d/{did}/w/{wid}/e/{eid}/features/featureid/{fid}`:

```json
{
  "btType": "BTFeatureDefinitionCall-1406",
  "rejectMicroversionSkew": false,
  "sourceMicroversion": "abc123",
  "feature": {
    "btType": "BTMFeature-134",
    "featureId": "FID0",
    "featureType": "extrude",
    "name": "Extrude 1",
    "parameters": [
      { "btType": "BTMParameterEnum-145",
        "parameterId": "endBound", "value": "BLIND" },
      { "btType": "BTMParameterQuantity-147",
        "parameterId": "depth", "expression": "50 mm" }
    ]
  }
}
```

Response (add/update) — the persisted feature plus its compute state:

```json
{
  "btType": "BTFeatureDefinitionCall-1406",
  "feature": { "btType": "BTMFeature-134", "featureId": "FID0", "...": "..." },
  "featureState": { "btType": "BTFeatureState-1688", "...": "..." },
  "sourceMicroversion": "def456"
}
```

`GET features` returns the same `BTMFeature-134` shape inside arrays:

```json
{
  "btType": "BTFeatureListResponse-2457",
  "rollbackIndex": -1,
  "sourceMicroversion": "abc123",
  "isComplete": true,
  "defaultFeatures": [ { "btType": "BTMFeature-134", "...": "..." } ],
  "features": [
    { "btType": "BTMFeature-134", "featureId": "FID0",
      "featureType": "extrude", "name": "Extrude 1",
      "parameters": [
        { "btType": "BTMParameterQuantity-147",
          "parameterId": "depth", "expression": "25 mm" }
      ] }
  ],
  "featureStates": {}
}
```

> Note: Onshape serialization sometimes nests each node under a `message` key;
> `onshape_edit.py` defensively unwraps it (`_unwrap`). Read fields off the
> unwrapped object.

## Recipe

Read-modify-write a single quantity, then re-GET to prove it stuck. READ-ONLY
against user docs — point writes at a scratch document. The runnable, HMAC-signed
implementation is `examples/onshape/onshape_edit.py`; `--self-test` proves the
full GET → mutate → POST → re-GET flow with no credentials (it spins an
in-process mock of the features API):

```bash
# creds-free proof the envelope round-trips (mock features API)
python3 examples/onshape/onshape_edit.py --self-test

# live: change the first extrude's depth on a scratch Part Studio URL
export ONSHAPE_ACCESS_KEY=... ONSHAPE_SECRET_KEY=...
python3 examples/onshape/onshape_edit.py \
  "https://cad.onshape.com/documents/<did>/w/<wid>/e/<eid>" "50 mm"
```

The flow it runs (and the one to replicate by hand):

1. `GET …/e/{eid}/features` → keep `sourceMicroversion`; find the target
   `BTMFeature-134` (match `featureType == "extrude"`) and its depth
   `BTMParameterQuantity-147` (`parameterId == "depth"`).
2. Mutate **only** `param["expression"]` on the fetched object; leave every
   other parameter in place.
3. `POST …/features/featureid/{fid}` with the whole feature wrapped in
   `BTFeatureDefinitionCall-1406`, echoing `sourceMicroversion`.
4. **Verify**: re-`GET …/features`, read the depth `expression` back, assert it
   equals the requested value. Optionally compare `…/massproperties` `volume`
   before/after to confirm the geometry actually recomputed.

Cross-links: @onshape/partstudios (the element + idtranslations), @onshape/api
(the high-level edit tool), @onshape/featurescript (queries & feature specs),
@onshape/auth (HMAC signing).
